Harvard students complete an adequate course of rest
All undergraduate students at Harvard University will attend a course this year to increase student rest. The course is a counterattack to the university’s thriving macho culture, where students weigh a long night with caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant of the basics of their own well-being.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University, who works in sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes that the course is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got an idea for the course after he lectured on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing about it now, in my last year of study?'
No one had ever told him about the need for a dream, which I thought was surprising," he said in an interview with Telegraph.
For the first time this year, a course will guide students about how proper sleep habits support academic and athletic performances and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Harvard Medical Faculty and Deputy Director of Health Services at the University of Harvard University, says that the university ended the course after hearing how students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the study week.
An hour-long course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented a picture of the dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, thus providing information on the effects of caffeine and light and the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performances and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know that this has no direct impact on student behaviour.
However, we believe that they have the right to know about these matters in exactly the same way as they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking," Professor Czeisler adds.
According to Professor Czeisler, all night long study marathons are still a proud subject, and modern technology and the growing pressures of students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Geting adequate and high quality sleep should be a secret weapon against stress, fatigue and anxiety among students, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state that resembles starvation in the brain, which is why people are constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler to plan the course after attending one of the courses he taught at Harvard in his first year last year.
He says that the course has opened his eyes and gave the impetus to organise a comprehensive course for all campus students.
He hopes that all postgraduate students will be able to complete a similar study package before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock to remind them not only of bedtime but also to wake up in the morning, and also to keep in mind the effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting on the daily rhythm, which may make it difficult to fall asleep.
