A new cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ the malignant cells and destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognise malignant cells as part of the treatment
The method is used to isolate resistant cells from the patient and to modify them in the laboratory.
After treatment, cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ the proteins typical of many cancers
The vaccine has given promising results in patients with different cancers.
For example, cancer cells in a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells.
The method isolates resistant cells from the patient and changes them in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of many cancers. The modified cells are finally injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, the United States, describes the method: "Our results indicate that this is a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "directs the growth of several types of cancer", explains Professor Berzofsky. "These include breast cancer and cancer of the ovaries, lungs and colon."
A similar approach — taking resistant cells from a patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells — has also produced results in treating a type of leukemia.
