HIV/AIDS: The number of new infections in China has increased by 14%
China has reported a 14% increase in the number of HIV-positive and AIDS-infected citizens.
According to health authorities, the virus affects the lives of more than 820 000 people in the country.
Approximately 40,000 new cases have been reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
A clear majority of new cases have been transmitted through sex, which means a change in previous statistics.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly through blood transfusions contaminated in some parts of China.
However, according to the Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan Province, HIV infections in this way have been reduced to almost zero.
One year later, however, the number of people infected with HIV and AIDS in China has risen by 100,000 cases.
HIV transmission via sex is an acute issue in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was devalued in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people has been reported to be widespread.
Studies have estimated that, due to conservative values in the country, between 70% and 90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry women.
Many of the diseases are due to inadequate protection in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese Government has promised to guarantee universal access to HIV medicines as part of its efforts to solve the problem.
