What is the Global Citizen Festival, and what has it done to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, the Global Citizen Festival in New York, is a music event with a performer guard as impressive as its mission: the eradication of poverty in the world.
The Global Citizen Festival, now held for the seventh time, will attract tens of thousands of people to the lawns of the Central Park in New York to listen to performers such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to make known the real objective of the event: the eradication of extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which started in 2012, is a continuation of the Global Powerty Project, an international advisory group aimed at eradicating poverty by increasing the number of people active in eradicating poverty.
In order to get a free ticket to an event (if not willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the public must carry out various tasks or "works", such as voluntary work, send an e-mail to the political decision-maker or make a call, or do any other action to raise awareness of the objectives of the project.
But how has Global Citizen been successful now that we have only 12 years to achieve this goal?
Does a free concert ticket have the idea of rewarding a real way to persuade people to take action, or is it just one ‘clactivism’ among others — a fantasy that the world can be changed by signing a web address or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen announces that it has registered more than 19 million "works" for different goals since 2011.
According to it, these actions have encouraged political decision-makers to announce commitments and principles that represent more than 37 billion dollars and have been used in a way that affects the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 commitments and declarations on the basis of which more than 10 billion dollars have already been spent or collected.
The group estimates that nearly 649 million people worldwide have already been affected by the funds achieved.
The main commitments include, for example, the Power of Nutrition, a group of investors and executives in the UK who are committed to "helping children develop to their full potential", which committed to providing 35 million dollars to Rwanda to end malnutrition in the country, after 4 700 TV sets had been sent to them by activists as a result of the Global Citizen campaign.
"Thanks to the British Government, donors, governments of different countries and to world citizens just like you, we can transfer social injustice and malnutrition to the history of the press," said Ambassador Tracey Ullman of the Power of Nutrition at a concert in London in 2018.
According to the Group, the British Government was also called upon to take action to improve the nutrition of mothers and children by over 5,000 acts, which have announced funding for the Power on Nutrition project, which will reach 5 million mothers and children.
One of the questions in the frequently asked questions column on the store's website is: "Why do you think we can put an end to extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen's answer: "The road will be long and difficult and many stumbling blocks lie ahead of us.
However, we will succeed, such as the great civil rights struggles and the moves against apartheid before us, because together we are stronger."
Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman are hosting a New York concert this year, and its star guard includes artists such as Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe.
