World Wide Web inventor plans to launch a new Internet counterattack on Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of World Wide Web, has launched a startup company to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee's open source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to decide where their data are stored and who has access to what information.
In an interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokes about Inrupt's intention to "rule the world".
"It has to be done now," he said, referring to his startup company.
"This is an historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own "personal data repository" or POD.
It can include contact lists, checklists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It is like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify all available on a single browser at the same time.
The unique thing about a personal data repository is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what type of data.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through information".
According to the CEO of the company, John Bruce, Inrupt’s idea is to provide resources, processes and the required skills to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently comprises Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some paid developers working with the project and a community of voluntary coders.
Technology developers around the world can create their own distributed applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website. This is all available from this week on.
Berners-Lee says that he and his team will not discuss with "Facebook and Google whether people should be offered a complete change in which all their business models are turned upside down overnight".
"We don't ask for their consent."
In an article published at the Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission was to provide commercial energy and ecosystem for the unity and quality of the new Solid network.
In 1994, Berners-Lee revolutionized the Internet by setting up the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been a powerful voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and leader of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute, even after the launch of Inrupt.
"I am extremely optimistic in view of the next era of the network," Berners-Lee added.
