Germany’s New Warship Delays Again
The latest frigate in the German fleet should have been introduced in 2014. The purpose of the vessel is to replace obsolete Cold War equipment, but it will not be introduced until next year because of faulty systems and explosive costs, the local media will tell.
According to a military spokesman who spoke to Die Zeit, the deployment of the ‘Rheinland-Pfalzin’, the new ‘Baden-Württemberg’-class first vessel has been postponed until the first half of 2019.
The ship was due to join the fleet in 2014, but worrying post-delivery problems have haunted an ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg class ships ordered by the fleet in 2007 are intended to replace the ageing Bremen class frigates.
According to the information available, they are equipped with an effective cannon, missile systems for the control of aircraft and surface vessels, and stealth technology such as radar reflectivity, infrared and acoustic signal detection.
Another important feature of the ship is its longer service interval – new frigates should be able to operate at sea for up to two years without visiting the home port.
However, constant delays mean that technology-driven warships – the purpose of which is said to be to improve Germany’s influence in the overseas territories – are already out of date when they enter the service, notes Die Zeit.
Last year, the unfortunate F125-fregat ended up in headlines when the German fleet formally refused to introduce the ship and returned it to Blohm & Voss in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned the ship after it has been delivered.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but in the German media there has been talk of essential "software and equipment failures" that make a warship unfit for combat tasks.
Software deficiencies are particularly relevant because the crew of Baden-Württemberg class ships is approximately 120, which is only half of the crew of Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it was found that the vessel is significantly overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the fleet’s ability to make subsequent updates.
It is believed that Rhineland-Palatinate, with its capacity of 7 000 tonnes, is twice as heavy as the equivalent class of ships used by Germany in World War II.
In addition to faulty equipment, the price tag for the whole project is also becoming a problem.
The price is said to have risen to a stunning amount of EUR 3.1 billion, compared with the original price of EUR 2.2 billion.
Problems with the introduction of new frigates have arisen as the German maritime authorities have recently been warned of shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, Director of the Defence Committee of the German Parliament, pointed out earlier this year that the fleet's usable vessels "are running low".
According to the Authority, the problem has grown over time due to the withdrawal of old vessels but no new ones have been submitted.
He deplored the fact that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates could have been used by the fleet.
The environmental organization is eavesdropping on the hidden lives of bats.
A new study in the Highlands of Scotland seeks to find out how bats use the terrain to hunt for food.
New research is hoped to shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and to guide future conservation measures.
Research carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland is carried out to monitor bats and dwarf bats, as well as earroats and water wings in the Inverewe Garden area of the Botanical Garden in Wester Ross.
The study places special storage devices at important points in the area to monitor the operation of bats during the period.
Workers and volunteers of the organisation also carry out mobile measurements using portable observation devices.
The frequency of the votes and the species at issue will be ensured by expert analysis.
Based on the results, a habitat map and report will be created in which bat behaviour can be presented in an image that reflects the scale of the area.
Rob Dewar, the organisation’s nature conservation advisor, hopes that the results will reveal which habitats are most important for bats and how different species exploit them.
This information will help in the planning of the habitat areas, such as the creation of meadows and the management of forest areas, taking bats and associated species into account.
The bat populations in Scotland and the whole of Great Britain have decreased considerably over the past 100 years.
Construction and construction work threaten the resting places and habitats of bats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as flypapers and certain chemicals used in building materials and attacks on pet cats.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, because of the nocturnal hunting practices, their ears are more beneficial in catching catch than in the eyes.
Bats use advanced echo detection techniques to detect insects and obstacles on their flight path.
National Trust for Scotland is an organisation dedicated to the protection of the rural environment that maintains more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76 000 hectares of land – and they take bats seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly conduct surveys, ramp inspections and, in some cases, animal rescue activities.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only reserve for the protection of bats in the countries of Dumfries and Threave Manor in Galloway, where eight of the ten bat species of Scotland are found.
According to farm manager David Thompson, the area is ideal for bats.
"Threave is very good for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings and trees and a good living environment overall.
We do not know everything about bats yet, so our work here and in other areas of the organization will help us to understand better what bats need to succeed."
He stresses the importance of checking the buildings for bats before embarking on refurbishment because the destruction of a single bat resting place can unintentionally cause the death of as many as 400 female bats and chicks and destroy an entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and killing, disturbing or destroying their resting places is prohibited.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official of the Bat Protection Agency, encourages the public to participate in the protection work.
He says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we still don't know how their populations are doing."
