Federal prosecutors in New York are seeking the death penalty for Sayfullo Saipov, a suspected terrorist attack in New York City that claimed eight lives, a rare sentence that has not been executed in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
According to the charge, Saipov, 30, used the Home Depot rental car in his October attack on the West Side Highway in the south of Manhattan, where he hit pedestrians and cyclists.
According to the notification of the application for the death penalty in the Southern Administrative Region of New York, the death penalty is possible if the prosecutors are able to prove that Saipov killed his eight victims "for intent" and caused serious physical injuries.
According to the court document, it is possible to put both of these charges to death.
Weeks after the attack, the federal court charged Saipovi with a 22-point charge involving eight murders to assist a terrorist organisation. Federal prosecutors typically use this crime title in cases of organised crime, and charges of violence and the destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack called for "substantial planning and preparation", the prosecutors noted and described the way in which Saipov carried out his actions "morbid, cruel and shameful."
"Sayfullo Habibullavic Saipov caused injuries, harm and loss to the families of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erliji, Herna Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco", states the affidavit.
Five of the victims were Argentine tourists.
Since the last time the court of the southern district of New York has issued the death penalty, it has been a decade.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of the murders of two drug traffickers, but was eventually sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The death penalty was last enforced in New York City in the federal case in 1953, when the couple Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were executed as convicted of a conspiracy for spying for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Both Rosenbergs were executed in an electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to the court records, Saipov, a citizen of Uzbekistan, showed no signs of remorse during the days and months following the attack.
He told the investigators what he was doing felt good, the police told him.
According to the charge, Saipov told the authorities that he had been inspired by his attack after watching ISIS videos on his phone.
The police said Saipov also wanted an ISIS ticket to his hospital room.
He answered a 22-point charge that he was innocent.
David Patton, one of Saipov's federal public defenders, said that the defense was "naturally disappointed" in the prosecution's decision.
"We believe that the decision to demand the death penalty, not recognition and life without the possibility of being released, is a solution which merely prolongs the trauma caused by these events to those concerned," said Patton.
Saipov’s defence had previously asked that he not be required to receive the death penalty.
