Red Tide flower situation: concentrations are falling in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there is a general decline in algae levels in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more fragmented algae areas are reported in the regions of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, possibly indicating a decrease in concentrations.
Red Tide algae bloom stretches along the coast about 130 miles from Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Ferries can be detected ten miles off the Hillsborough County coast, but there are fewer than last week.
Red Tide flowering has also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations were reported on the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, ranging from low to high levels on the coasts of Hillsborough County, from high background concentrations in Manate and Sarasota County, from moderate background concentrations in Charlotte County and from high background concentrations in the coasts of Lee District Court and from low levels in Collier County.
Respiratory symptoms are still reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the last week, no reports of respiratory symptoms occurred in the northwest of Florida.
